":"1250","1271":"1271","1281":"1281","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","1314":"1314","1336":"1336","about 1305":"circa 1305","1355":"1355","1310":"1310","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","<, Yaxley, Suffolk>, England":"Yaxley, Suffolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Yaxley, Suffolk, England":"Yaxley, Suffolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1281–Abt 1314":"1281–about 1314","1271–1330":"1271–1330","1281–1314":"1281–1314","1280–1336":"1280–1336","1285–Female":"1285–Deceased","1314–1355":"1314–1355","1250–1310":"1250–1310","1330":"1330","Abt 1314":"about 1314","Cir 1270-1280":"from 1270 to 1280","1285":"1285","1250":"1250","1271":"1271","1281":"1281","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","1314":"1314","1336":"1336","about 1305":"about 1305","1355":"1355","1310":"1310","England":"England, United Kingdom","<, Yaxley, Suffolk>, England":"Yaxley, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Yaxley, Suffolk, England":"Yaxley, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Shearman","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Sherman  . The surname is also established in Ireland (Kilkenny)."],"variants":[{"name":"Sherman","meanings":["English (London): occupational name denoting someone who used shears to trim the surface of finished cloth and remove excessive nap, from Middle English <i>sherman</i>, <i>shirman</i>, <i>sharman</i> ‘shearman’.","Americanized form of North German <b>Schürmann</b> (see   Schuermann  ) and of German or Jewish (Ashkenazic)   Schermann  .","Jewish (Ashkenazic): occupational name for a tailor, from Yiddish <i>sher</i> ‘scissors’ + <i>man</i> ‘man’."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"le","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["1  ♂ ‘Profit’ or ‘sharp’.","2  ♀, ♂ ‘Upright’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":9,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Robert le Shearman was born in 1281, in Yaxley, Suffolk, England, his father, Richard LeShearman, was 31 and his mother, Mrs. Christina Le Shearman, was 31. He married Lady Alice de Joinville about 1305, in Yaxley, Suffolk, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died about 1314, in Yaxley, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 34."},"et":{"1281–Abt 1314":"1281–umbes 1314","1271–1330":"1271–1330","1281–1314":"1281–1314","1280–1336":"1280–1336","1285–Female":"1285–Surnud","1314–1355":"1314–1355","1250–1310":"1250–1310","1330":"1330","Abt 1314":"umbes 1314","Cir 1270-1280":"1270 kuni 1280","1285":"1285","1250":"1250","1271":"1271","1281":"1281","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","1314":"1314","1336":"1336","about 1305":"umbes 1305","1355":"1355","1310":"1310","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","<, Yaxley, Suffolk>, Engla